# Feature-Sliced Design (FSD)

## Layers and dependency direction
Allowed direction only:
`app -> processes -> pages -> widgets -> features -> entities -> shared`

- A lower layer MUST NOT import from a higher layer.
- Cross-slice imports MUST go through the slice public API (`index.ts` / `index.tsx`).

## Public API only (no deep imports)
- ✅ `import { LoginForm } from '@/features/auth-by-email'`
- ❌ `import { LoginForm } from '@/features/auth-by-email/ui/LoginForm'`

## Same-layer boundaries
- Same-layer slices MUST NOT import each other directly (only via public API + documented exception).

## Slice structure
Each slice is a folder like `features/auth-by-email`, `entities/user`.
Allowed segments: `ui/`, `model/`, `api/`, `lib/`, `config/`, `assets/`.

## Placement rules
- `shared/`: generic ui-kit, utils, base api, config (no business meaning)
- `entities/`: domain objects (User/Product) + their ui/model/api
- `features/`: user actions (login, add-to-cart)
- `widgets/`: composed blocks (Header, Sidebar)
- `pages/`: route composition, minimal logic
- `processes/`: long flows across pages/features
- `app/`: providers, store setup, app initialization

## Next.js App Router guidance
- Keep route files thin: compose `widgets/features/entities`.
- Prefer Server Components; add `use client` only for leaf UI needing browser APIs.